Title: Don't Teach Statistics in High School
Description: In recent years, there have been more and more calls to prioritize statistics in high-school math curricula. The rationale is that unlike, say, calculus, statistics is supposedly much more applicable in everyday life. Sounds nice, but what does that really mean? Computing averages? Hell yeah, that’s useful1! But most of the things that are taught in a typical (AP, A-level, IB) high-school stats course are not only of little practical value, but also—and more importantly—misleading. Statistics is one of very few subjects where studying it for a short time leads to poorer intuition about the real world than not having studied it at all.
